Measure Type: Higher rates are better for this measure
Rate Definition: Percentage with a PCP Visit in the Past Year: Ages 25 Months to 6 Years
Source: Mathematica analysis of MACPro reports for the FFY 2019 reporting cycle as of May 31, 2020.
State Specific Comments: Rates include PCCM and managed care populations (5 MCOs), representing 71 percent of the population. Rates exclude FFS population, representing 29 percent of the population, but the majority of the FFS beneficiaries would not have been measure-eligible, including children who have other primary insurance, children with limited Medicaid benefits, children in premium assistance programs, new enrollees who have not yet enrolled in an MCO, and children in state custody. State attributes decline in denominator to transition of beneficiaries from managed care to ACO program during the measurement period, reducing the number of beneficiaries who met continuous enrollment requirements for FFY 2019.

Domain: Primary Care Access and Preventive Care
Measure Name: Developmental Screening in the First Three Years of Life: Ages 0 to 3
Measure Type: Higher rates are better for this measure
Rate Definition: Percentage Screened for Risk of Developmental, Behavioral, and Social Delays Using a Standardized Screening Tool: Ages 0 to 3
Source: Mathematica analysis of MACPro reports for the FFY 2019 reporting cycle as of May 31, 2020.
State Specific Comments: Rate includes PCCM and managed care populations (5 MCOs), representing 71 percent of the population. Rate excludes FFS population, representing 29 percent of the population, but the majority of the FFS beneficiaries would not have been measure-eligible, including children who have other primary insurance, children with limited Medicaid benefits, children in premium assistance programs, new enrollees who have not yet enrolled in an MCO, and children in state custody. State requires that providers offer a behavioral health screening to all children ages 0 to 21 using a standardized screening tool selected from a state-approved list of screening tools, but the list includes global and non-global screenings. As a result, the state’s method deviates from Core Set specifications because it cannot differentiate between global and non-global screenings. Based on previous studies, the state believes that global screening tools account for a large percentage of the conducted screenings.

State Specific Comments: CMS calculated rate using CDC WONDER data.

Measure Name: Prenatal and Postpartum Care: Timeliness of Prenatal Care
Measure Type: Higher rates are better for this measure
Rate Definition: Percentage of Women Delivering a Live Birth with a Prenatal Care Visit in the First Trimester or within 42 Days of Enrollment in Medicaid or CHIP
Source: Mathematica analysis of MACPro reports for the FFY 2019 reporting cycle as of May 31, 2020.
State Specific Comments: Rate includes FFS, PCCM, and managed care populations (5 MCOs). Rate excludes Medicare-Medicaid Dual Eligibles and those with full third-party liability. State used vital records as an additional source for indication of first trimester care or date of first prenatal visit. State evaluated first trimester based on gestational age at birth in addition to the specified 176-280 days before delivery. Denominator excludes records with missing birth certificate information about when prenatal care began that also had no prenatal care claims within 42 days of Medicaid enrollment (about 4.9 percent of births). Rate was calculated using the 15th of the month as the eligibility start date. Rate includes the following taxonomy codes as service provider to identify prenatal care and not emergent care: Family Medicine, General Practice, OB/GYN, Maternal & Fetal Medicine, Midwife, Lay Midwife, Advanced Practice Midwife, Nurse Practitioner, Family Nurse Practitioner, Women's Health Nurse Practitioner, OB/GYN Nurse Practitioner, Primary Care Nurse Practitioner, Physician Assistant, and Physician Assistant-Medical.

Measure Name: Initiation and Engagement of Alcohol and Other Drug Abuse or Dependence Treatment: Age 18 and Older
Measure Type: Higher rates are better for this measure
Rate Definition: Percentage with a New Episode of Alcohol Abuse or Dependence who Initiated Alcohol or Other Drug Treatment within 14 Days of the Diagnosis: Ages 18 to 64
Source: Mathematica analysis of MACPro reports for the FFY 2019 reporting cycle as of May 31, 2020.
State Specific Comments: Rates include statewide 1115 waiver population enrolled in a public non-risk prepaid inpatient health plan population, representing the total Medicaid population. Rates exclude Medicare-Medicaid Dual Eligibles. State modified measure to reflect that state Medicaid agency pays for substance abuse treatment services as a monthly unit of bundled treatment services. Rates include residential substance abuse treatment as initiation or engagement events where appropriate following the HEDIS specifications for sub-acute inpatient care. When the residential substance abuse treatment is the index, both index and initiation dates are set as the last day of residential substance abuse treatment. If there is no gap in services, the next month is counted as engagement. Rates were validated by the state's EQRO.
